    <!-- Key Finding Box -->
    <div style="padding:1rem;background:#111;border-radius:8px;margin-bottom:2rem;border:1px solid #333;">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 0.5rem;color:#f90;">Key Finding: decodeURI() vs decodeURIComponent()</h3>
      <p style="margin:0 0 0.5rem;color:#ccc;line-height:1.7;">
        Astro uses <code>decodeURI()</code> (not <code>decodeURIComponent()</code>) to decode route params.
        <br/>
        <code>decodeURI()</code> does <strong>NOT</strong> decode reserved characters like <code>/</code> (i.e., <code>%2F</code> stays <code>%2F</code>).
        <br/>
        But it <strong>DOES</strong> decode percent-encoded letters: <span style="color:#f44;"><code>%61</code> → <code>a</code></span>.
      </p>
      <p style="margin:0 0 0.5rem;color:#ccc;line-height:1.7;">
        <strong>CVE-2025-64765</strong>: Middleware sees <code>/admin</code> check against <code>Astro.url.pathname</code>.
        A request to <code>/%61dmin</code> passes the middleware check (<code>/%61dmin</code> !== <code>/admin</code>),
        but Astro then decodes it with <code>decodeURI()</code> before routing — so the page still loads.
        <br/>
        <span style="color:#f44;">Bypass: <code>/%61dmin</code> — letters decode, slashes don't.</span>
      </p>
      <p style="margin:0;color:#888;font-size:0.85rem;">
        Bottom line: <code>%2F</code> path traversal via params is blocked by <code>decodeURI()</code>.
        But <code>searchParams</code>, <code>location.hash</code>, and <code>set:html</code> sinks are still critical-risk.
        And middleware bypasses work via letter encoding.
      </p>
    </div>

